description: What I Mean By Mercy (WIMBM) is a short film series and a companion to 3 poems written as a conceptualization of what mercy is and could be.  A holy word, a war word, a word moonlighting with love and a kind of devotion--mercy is an abstraction and a muse of burgeoning arts incubator, Mother Mercy. WIMBM was a collaborative effort showcasing the directorial debut of JME, poet and founder of Mother Mercy, as well as the vision of Amin Aliabadi, director of part I and co-director of part II. David Hill, editor and director of photography materialized the musings. This series, produced by Mother Mercy, grapples with how we choose to live mercifully with ourselves & with others.
title: GlobeDocs Presents: 'What I Mean By Mercy'

description: This installment focuses on learning to set boundaries with the people we love. What if six friends want to hang out for a July 4th BBQ? What if someone wants to come inside our homes but we’re not comfortable with that? Adults and kids need to know how to explain their boundaries, but sometimes that’s so hard. The panelists talk about good language to use, how to avoid judging the needs of others, and how we can be social without making each other uncomfortable.

description: This episode of Taking Care is a Q&A with Boston College’s David Blustein, who studies work and psychology – as in, what unemployment means to people, and how our jobs contribute to our mental health. He wrote a book called “The Importance of Work in an Age of Uncertainty," which came out in 2019 – before this pandemic. Blustein talks to Love Letters columnist Meredith Goldstein about how we can take care of ourselves if we’re working, out of work, deemed essential (and in harm’s way), or considering a career change now that the world and our priorities have shifted. Get David's book here.
title: 9.Taking Care with Meredith Goldstein

description: Twitter is what’s happening and what people are talking about, all around the world. From breaking news and entertainment, to sports and politics. If it's happening, it's happening first on Twitter. First and foremost, Twitter is a platform for news. Peter Greenberger, Global Director of News, will outline how the platform is connecting the dots between newsrooms and developers.  You will also hear from the Twitter Platform team about the future of the @TwitterAPI, highlighting recent improvements (and new features) to the Direct Message APIs. We'll dive into specific use cases for our new data platform and publisher tools, as well. We're excited to share Twitter’s tools with the NYC community so that we can continue to better innovate and build, together.

description: The Globe asked best-selling author Ben Mezrich to write a novella, a work of fiction, to be published exclusively in the Globe and on Globe.com.
